node.text: Bhaktapur, what is left of it after had suffered from a very devastated 2015 earthquake which caused loss of lives. Located 20km from Kathmandu, Bhaktapur is known as ‘City of Devotees’, which filled with monuments, most of terra-cotta with carved wood columns, palaces and temples with elaborate carvings, gilded roofs and open courtyards

Kathamandu durbar square, also known as basantapur darbar kshetra; which located at the center of kathmandu is one of the UNESCO world heritage sites. The restoration are made for the several buildings which have suffered the 7.8 magnitude earthquake in 2015. The traditional architecture of the buildings are spectacular with its intricate wood carvings and rich history which dated back to almost 1000 years ago

As one of the UNESCO World Heritage sites, Qutub Minar is the tallest brick minaret in the world at a height of 72.5m. The whole structure was built using red sandstone and was carved from Quran verses which potrays Indo-Mughal architecture

Hawa Mahal or known as Palace of the Winds was built by Maharaja Sawai Pratap Singh in 1799 and intended for the royal women to enjoy the events and festivals in the street without being seen by norm people. The architecture style of this Hawa Mahal was by blending the Hindu Rajput architecture and the Islamic Mughal architecture. The high screen wall was made from pink and red sandstone to reflect the Jaipur’s pride pink city

The Mosque of Taj Mahal is located at the left side of Taj Mahal, mirrored the guest pavilion and it is facing the Mecca (qibla). Together both of them provide a perfect symmetrical balance to the architecture of the whole of Taj Mahal. The exterior of the mosque was constructed with red sandstone inlaid with white rectangular marble. The interior of the mosque are inscribed with delicate calligraphy citing the name Allah and quotations from Quran (Surah As-Shams). The only differences with guest pavilion are the Mihrab and Minbar (praying area). Aside, there lies a small stone enclosed space, which served as a temporary grave where the remains of Mumtaz Mahal that were kept for some time when they were first brought to Agra, until the mausoleum was built

The Lotus Gate in an inner courtyard called Pritam Niwas Chowk, in the southwest of City Palace is one of the 4 doors that represents seasons and gods; which represented the summer and it is dedicated to Shiva and Parvati

It took us 12 hours journey by car from Chandigarh to witness this beauty of Solang Valley of Manali. We were quite disappointed because there wasn’t snow this year around. Chand Baori (step well) was built by King Chanda and it was dedicated to Hashat Mata, Goddess of Joy and Happiness. Chand Baori was intended to conserve as much water as possible during the draught season. At the bottom of the well, the air constantly remains 5-6 degrees cooler than at the surface, and Chand Baori was used as a community gathering place for locals during periods of intense heat. Chand Baori consists of 3,500 narrow steps over 13 stories and it extends approximately 30 m (100 ft) into the ground making it one of the deepest and largest stepwells in India

“Wanderlust, the very strong or irresistible impulse to travel, is adopted untouched from the German, presumably because it couldn’t be improved upon. Workarounds like the French passion du voyage don’t quite capture the same meaning. Wanderlust is not a passion for travel exactly; it’s something more animal and more fickle – something more like lust. We don’t lust after very many things in life. We don’t need words like worklust or homemakinglust. But travel? Anatole Broyard put it perfect in his essay Being There: Travel is like adultery: ‘One is always tempted to be unfaithful to one’s own country. To have imagination is inevitably to be dissatisfied with where you live…in our wanderlust, we are lovers looking for consummation.’” Elisabeth Eaves
